      },
      "lineNbr": 48,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-06-15T15:40:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I agree, the fact that we use an array of chars to store the data is an implementation detail, the API should be more generic than that.",
      "parentUuid": "b47a9131_b4e246db",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 48,
        "startChar": 44,
        "endLine": 48,
        "endChar": 54
      },
      "revId": "1c55b09cb0c861febdac06ad9e533fbae33addce",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b47a9131_540a0218",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/shared/OpenglCodecCommon/GLDecoderContextData.h",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 48,
      "author": {
        "id": 1099352
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-06-15T16:22:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "OK, I take it back.  I was arguing to myself that since the len argument gave a byte length, that it was already committed to being considered, in the interface, as an array of bytes, so that the void* wasn\u0027t actually buying you anything.  But I guess it does buy you something: if you had a struct S, and a \"S s;\", then you could call this with\n  storePointerData(loc, \u0026s, sizeof(S))\nwhereas the char* version would require a cast:\n  storePointerData(loc, reinterpret_cast\u003cchar*\u003e(\u0026s), sizeof(S))\nNote that a cast back to S is necessary in the pointerData call that retrieves the value in either case, so it wouldn\u0027t make a difference there.\n\nBut I\u0027ll grant that avoiding a reinterpret_cast on calls is sufficient reason to use void* in the interface, and do the casts to/from char* in the implementation.",
      "parentUuid": "7468199f_997abb5f",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 48,
        "startChar": 44,
        "endLine": 48,
        "endChar": 54
      },
      "revId": "1c55b09cb0c861febdac06ad9e533fbae33addce",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8f09f4df_2fecd9fc",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/shared/OpenglCodecCommon/GLDecoderContextData.h",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 71,
      "author": {
        "id": 1099352
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-06-13T17:19:54Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "There may be a bug here.  In the old code, it seems like kMaxVertexAttributes is really kind of misnamed: it\u0027s used as a default, and nothing ever enforces that it\u0027s the max.  You could call the GLDecoderContextData with numLocaions \u003d 128, for example.  Use of the fixed-size std::Array really does make it a max.\n\nSo it seems to me that you either have to go back to the old use of a vector, or convince me that the old code could have asserted in the constructor that numLocations \u003c\u003d kMaxVertexAttributes.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 71,
        "startChar": 34,
        "endLine": 71,
        "endChar": 54
      },
      "revId": "1c55b09cb0c861febdac06ad9e533fbae33addce",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8f09f4df_84018731",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/shared/OpenglCodecCommon/GLDecoderContextData.h",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 71,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-06-13T17:44:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That could be a good idea, but I think the situation right now is that kMaxVertexAttributes (64) is \u003e\u003e GL_MAX_VERTEX_ATTRIBS in any situations with existing GPU hardware. So far it looks like it\u0027s just 16 all the time, and most apps really use like 4. These vertex attributes are used to assign different abstract coordinates to vertices like position, color, normal, texture coordinate (there we go, 4). You might be using multiple sets of texture coordinates if you are doing fancy blending work, but never anything close to or above 16 AFAIK.\n\nStrictly speaking, yeah the max vertex attributes could be so high that we\u0027d need to update kMaxVertexAttributes, but that situation hasn\u0027t shown up at all. Plus, we only call the GLDecoderContextData ctor with kMaxVertexAttributes.",
      "parentUuid": "8f09f4df_2fecd9fc",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 71,
        "startChar": 34,
        "endLine": 71,
        "endChar": 54
      },
      "revId": "1c55b09cb0c861febdac06ad9e533fbae33addce",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8f09f4df_84b3474d",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/shared/OpenglCodecCommon/GLDecoderContextData.h",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 71,
      "author": {
        "id": 1099352
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-06-13T18:05:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "OK, good to hear that it probably wouldn\u0027t be a bug.\n\nI\u0027m still a little nervous about converting code that would have worked for any value of numLocations into code with a fixed limit.  But if the constructor is only ever called with the default argument (as it must be if eliminating it compiles), then I guess it\u0027s only a theoretical problem.",
      "parentUuid": "8f09f4df_84018731",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 71,
        "startChar": 34,
        "endLine": 71,
        "endChar": 54
      },
      "revId": "1c55b09cb0c861febdac06ad9e533fbae33addce",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
